ot a minor one. he joined the" b'expedition as a commander of the large kuwaiti fleet and was the first' b'to use its guns against the besieged town of al-qatif. had it not been' b'for this bombardment by the kuwaiti fleet, al-qatif obviously would' b'not have surrendered in a mere three hours.' b'' b'in relation to this, a question arises as to why the ottoman warships' b'refrained from participating in the bombardment. the answer lies in' b'reports relating to the political movements that preceded accounts of' b'the progress of the expedition. because the ottomans were unwilling to' b'jeopardize the maritime peace imposed by britain in the area, the' b'sultan and the pasha promised their warships would not be used in the' b"war against su'ud or any sheikh in the war zone. kuwait, which was not" b'a party to the above-mentioned treaty of was under no such' b'obligation especially since the expedition was not directed against' b'those who had signed it.' b'' b'' b'[ from the above text, we can see that kuwait was not part of the' b'ottomans or the british colonies. for more details about the mentioned' b'expedition, please check out the source of the above text:' b'' b'the modern history of kuwait, by ahmed abu-hakima, mcgill' b'university, canada b'' b'---' b'' b'independent kuwait--2' b'' b'this is another article of a series of articles that testify to the' b'independence of kuwait throughout its history from both iraq and the' b'ottomans.' b'' b'the following text discusses a dispute on an estate called sufiyya in zubair,' b'iraq, between the sheikh of kuwait and al-zuhair tribe in zubair.' b'' b'in trouble developed over the possession by sheikh sabah of the' b'estate which was [purchased] by his father, sheikh jabir, in this' b"property was sequestered by a turkish qa'immaqam [representative] on" b'the basis of a claim by the al-zuhair that the vendor had been the' b'owner of a share and not of the n 100e sufiyya. at the same time,' b'sheikh sabah was required to expel from other lands owned by him at' b'the island of fao some cultivators who had immigrated from persian' b'territory.' b'' b'it should be recalled that the turkish officials from the start' b'showed strong prejudice in favor of the zuhair claimants. abdulla ibn' b'sabah, the eldest son of the ruler of kuwait who went to basra as his' b"father's agent in the case, narrowly escaped being thrown into jail" b'upon his refusal to make a payment amounting to the value of seven' b'years produce which the ottoman authorities deemed the plaintiffs were' b'entitled to receive.' b'' b'eventually, the dispute was settled by the wali [governor] of baghdad' b'in favor of the sheikh of kuwait. the decision of the governor of' b'basra in favor of the sheikh was apparently made for various reasons.' b'some writers think that the governor wanted to win abdulla over to the' b'turkish side, and suggest that the governor, namiq pasha, even offered' b"him the title of qa'immaqam, which he declined. nevertheless, the" b'proceedings of the turks in this case were regarded by the inhabitants' b'of kuwait as attempts to cause a confrontation with zubair. it seems' b'that they had anticipated a conflict and according to reports by the' b'british agent at basra, the people of kuwait were prepared to a man to' b'abandon their town rather than submit to turkish rule. lorimer suggests' b"that the final order of namiq pasha, upholding the kuwait sheikh's" b'title to sufiyya, was perhaps due to a report that sheikh sabah,' b'``with the object of attacking zubair if the decision should go' b'against him, had obtained a promise of countenance and armed support' b"from the wahhabi amir.''" b'' b'in addition to this legal matter with zubair, kuwait had had other' b'problems with basra whose courts tried to jail abdulla ibn sabah, as' b"explained above. however, kuwait's relations with the ottoman" b'mutasallims of basra had at times been amicable and in several' b'instances, those mutasallims even sought refuge at kuwait when' b'pressured by the pashas of baghdad who exercised control over them.' b'' b'[ source: the modern history of kuwait, by ahmed abu-hakima,' b'mcgill university, canada b'' b'---' b'' b'independent kuwait--3' b'' b'this is another article that testifies to the' b'independence of kuwait throughout its history from both iraq and the' b'ottomans.' b'' b'' b'when pelly [colonel pelly, the british resident in the gulf] visited kuwait' b'for the first time on march he was' b'met at jahra by sheikh mubarak, the second son of the ruler, sheikh' b'sabah. just before he reached kuwait town on march he was met by' b'sheikh abdulla, the eldest son and heir apparent, who accompanied him' b"to the town gate on their way to ``a very good home,'' which had been" b"prepared for pelly and his companions. ``scarcely had we entered it,''" b"says pelly, ``when sheikh sabah himself came.''" b"this description of pelly's reception indicates that to a certain" b'degree it was run according to protocol.' b'' b'the government system of kuwait and administration of justice were the' b"subject of comments made by pelly. ``the government is patriarchal,''" b'says pelly, ``the sheikh managing the political, and the cazee [qadi]' b'the judicial departments. the sheikh himself would submit to the' b"cazee's decision.'' punishment was rarely inflicted. ``indeed, there" b'seems little government interference anywhere, and little need of an' b"army.'' pelly in admiration of how the sheikh ran the affairs of the" b'country, retold the following remark which the sheikh had made to him:' b'' b'when my father was nearly years old, he called me and said, ``i' b'shall soon die. i have made no fortune, and can leave you no money,' b'but i have made many and true friends, grapple them. while other' b'states around the gulf have fallen off from injustice or' b'ill-government, mine has gone on [flourishing]. hold to my policy, and' b'though you are surrounded by desert, and pre