 be looked upon as an' b"indication of self-confidence; an outcome of kuwait's independence" b'from foreign powers. it corroborates the fact that kuwait, if' b'necessary, was prepared to defend itself against more powerful' b'neighbors.' b'' b'this defense depended not only on the walls of the city, but also on' b'bedouin tribes in its neighborhood and a merchant fleet equipped with' b'the necessary guns comparable to other arab fleets of the time.' b'' b"as to kuwait's position between and one can safely state" b'that it managed to maintain a neutral policy with regard to the' b'struggling wahhabis and egyptians. relations with the british and' b'even with the pasha of baghdad continued on good terms.' b'' b'[ source: the modern history of kuwait, by ahmed abu-hakima,' b'mcgill university, canada b'' b'---' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'they were trying to recover land they believed' b'was theirs, much like the argentines in the faulklands. the kuwaitis pushed' b"just a little too far by taking iraqi oil and saddam thought he'd settle" b'the dispute the old fashioned way...' b'' b'are you really this cartoonish? or do you seriously believe this? if' b'so, please post your proof.' b'' b'everybody would have been much better off had they left the reunited iraq' b'together and concentrated on taking out saddam. a strong, united iraq with' b'an elected government would have gone a long way to ridding the world of' b'the feudal dictatorships in the gulf.' b'' b'are standards at uwisc dropping? since when has iraq *ever* had an' b'"elected" government?' b'' 